SIMPLE: prolong
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prolong
<hw>Pro*long"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Prolonged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Prolonging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>prolonger</ets>, L. <ets>prolongare</ets>; <ets>pro</ets> before,
forth + <ets>longus</ets> long. See <er>Long</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and
cf. <er>Prolongate</er>, <er>Purloin</er>. ]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To extend in space or length; <as>as, to
<ex>prolong</ex> a line</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lengthen in time; to extend the duration of; to
draw out; to continue; <as>as, to <ex>prolong</ex> one's
days</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Prolong</qex> awhile the traitor's life.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The unhappy queen with talk <qex>prolonged</qex> the night.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To put off to a distant time; to postpone.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prolongable</ent>⟦br⟧
